00:00:26.210 --> 00:00:29.660
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Let's do
a little general discussion

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:33.200
of some of the political
issues that we will encounter.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:42.020
This is a-- if you read
why there are governments,

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:47.790
if you read what governments say
about why they are established,

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:50.810
you get very
high-flown language.

00:00:50.810 --> 00:00:54.810
This is The Declaration of
Independence, life, liberty,

00:00:54.810 --> 00:00:56.750
and the pursuit of happiness.

00:00:56.750 --> 00:01:01.130
Governments are to
assure those rights.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:06.040
This is The Constitution,
a little less high-flying--

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:08.950
establish justice, ensure
domestic tranquility,

00:01:08.950 --> 00:01:12.550
provide for the common defense,
promote the general welfare,

00:01:12.550 --> 00:01:14.050
and secure the
blessings of liberty.

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:17.050
You will notice that we
have domestic tranquility,

00:01:17.050 --> 00:01:21.010
common defense, things
that are a little less

00:01:21.010 --> 00:01:25.353
high-flowing than life, liberty,
and the pursuit of happiness.

00:01:25.353 --> 00:01:27.020
Does anybody know
where this comes from?

00:01:30.930 --> 00:01:34.200
This is the law
that it's actually

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:36.960
an act the English
government that sets up

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:40.470
Canada as a separate state.

00:01:40.470 --> 00:01:43.530
Peace, order, and good
government-- somewhat different

00:01:43.530 --> 00:01:47.880
emphasis than life, liberty,
and the pursuit of happiness.

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:50.010
If you look at--

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:52.950
lots of other governments
don't write down--

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:57.540
or lots of other countries, lots
of regimes, postrevolutionary,

00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:01.560
Henry VIII, Ivan the Terrible,
Khmer Rouge, Joseph Stalin,

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:06.240
Adolf Hitler would not
write statements like that.

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:07.500
But they had goals.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:10.340
They have goals.

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:15.180
A key element of a
functioning government

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:19.570
is a near monopoly
on the use of force.

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:23.740
If you think about it, when
you think about Somalia

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:29.210
is a failed state, or
Libya is a failing state

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:30.680
not that long ago.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:35.000
What broke was the monopoly
on the use of deadly force--

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.670
near monopoly-- near monopoly.

00:02:37.670 --> 00:02:40.250
Is Syria a failed state yet?

00:02:40.250 --> 00:02:42.360
Probably not.

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:43.650
Is it en route?

00:02:43.650 --> 00:02:45.330
Maybe.

00:02:45.330 --> 00:02:50.630
But that's-- every government
that's really a government--

00:02:50.630 --> 00:02:54.990
really a government-- has a
monopoly on the use of force.

00:02:54.990 --> 00:03:00.890
It also has-- governments
tend to have legitimacy.

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:04.100
That is to say,
even in North Korea,

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:08.150
people aren't followed
around by a man with a gun.

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:15.590
People follow orders without
the use of force, generally--

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:17.650
generally.

00:03:17.650 --> 00:03:22.450
Legitimacy can come from
a number of sources.

00:03:22.450 --> 00:03:27.620
Again, if you think
about it in the abstract,

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:32.680
the US government probably gets
its legitimacy from the fact

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:35.560
that most people think
the processes followed

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:37.750
are reasonably fair.

00:03:37.750 --> 00:03:39.820
You might not have
liked the decision

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:43.450
in Bush versus Gore that
gave the election to Bush,

00:03:43.450 --> 00:03:45.580
but it followed
a certain process

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.900
and, yeah, you didn't like it,
but fundamentally, the process

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:50.412
was OK.

00:03:50.412 --> 00:03:52.870
You don't like the Bills that
come out of Congress, but you

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:54.640
know how people are elected--

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:57.370
blah, blah, blah.

00:03:57.370 --> 00:04:00.040
In the days of the
divine right of kings,

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:01.870
legitimacy came
from someplace else.

00:04:01.870 --> 00:04:05.980
Legitimacy came from the fact
that that king was the king.

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:09.050
And God said, he's the king.

00:04:09.050 --> 00:04:10.710
Do what he says.

00:04:10.710 --> 00:04:12.460
That's a pretty good
source of legitimacy.

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:15.670
Or you could have
a government that's

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:21.519
arbitrary, doesn't
have divine rights,

00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:25.610
but is doing things
that people like.

00:04:25.610 --> 00:04:30.140
You might ask, why was
the Hitler government--

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:33.180
why did it have
legitimacy in Germany?

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:35.190
Because the variety
of the goals it

00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:37.910
was pursuing were popular goals.

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:40.550
Was the process that
put it in office fair?

00:04:40.550 --> 00:04:42.520
Not really.

00:04:42.520 --> 00:04:46.450
Was Adolf Hitler
divinely endorsed?

00:04:46.450 --> 00:04:48.400
Not really.

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:50.830
But restoring
German self-respect,

00:04:50.830 --> 00:04:53.060
expanding the territory
of the country,

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:56.313
making it a power again,
et cetera, et cetera,

00:04:56.313 --> 00:04:57.355
those were popular goals.

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:03.270
And sometimes-- North Korea--

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:07.090
you have legitimacy
because the consequences

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:11.110
of not following orders
are pretty terrible.

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:13.800
So you follow orders.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.370
Governments also have
policies and a process

00:05:17.370 --> 00:05:19.530
for changing them.

00:05:19.530 --> 00:05:22.750
I want to spend just
a couple of minutes

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:25.420
about how the market system--

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:29.110
the market, which you
all studied in economics,

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:32.620
differs from the political
world, which we will

00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:34.255
be spending some time on here.

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:43.830
In the market, we think
of individuals or firms

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:46.490
pursuing self-interest.

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:49.440
That happens in the
political world.

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:52.650
But what also happens in
the political world is, A,

00:05:52.650 --> 00:05:56.360
groups are involved,
not just individuals--

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:59.750
parties, interest groups,
trade associations,

00:05:59.750 --> 00:06:01.430
industries acting together.

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:07.560
And you see the pursuit
both of self-interest

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:12.100
and have different views
of the public interest.

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:17.020
Because in the market--

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:18.800
right-- you make
decisions for yourself,

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:20.380
firm makes decisions for itself.

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:24.140
In the political
world most decisions

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:26.570
are for the community.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:30.190
So the question is not
only what's good for me--

00:06:30.190 --> 00:06:32.683
that matters, obviously--

00:06:32.683 --> 00:06:34.100
but what's good
for the community.

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:37.170
How do I think a
government should work?

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:39.470
How do I think a
community, a state,

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:41.750
a country should be organized?

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:45.470
What goals should it pursue?

00:06:45.470 --> 00:06:51.770
That gets us to the
question of ideology.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:58.380
In the market,
individual decisions

00:06:58.380 --> 00:07:01.800
are driven by
individual preferences.

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:05.760
In the political world,
ideology matters.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:11.580
Different views of how
the state should operate,

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:13.490
how society should
work, and what

00:07:13.490 --> 00:07:16.760
arrangements should be adopted.

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:18.410
So you and I might,
for instance,

00:07:18.410 --> 00:07:25.110
agree that society should
take care of poor people--

00:07:25.110 --> 00:07:27.980
or that poor people
should be taken care of.

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:30.200
People on the market
side might say, yeah,

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:32.600
that's what families are for.

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:36.140
That's how the state should be
organized to achieve that goal,

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:39.080
is families should understand
that that's their duty to take

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:42.120
care of poor relatives
and poor friends.

00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:44.620
People on the state
side might, say, well,

00:07:44.620 --> 00:07:48.730
that's all well and good,
but that won't work.

00:07:48.730 --> 00:07:50.290
That won't work.

00:07:50.290 --> 00:07:54.990
You might have different
goals, of course.

00:07:54.990 --> 00:07:58.020
People on the market
side might say,

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:02.880
the notion that the poor should
be taken care of is a bad idea.

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:04.747
It'll rob them of incentives.

00:08:04.747 --> 00:08:06.330
And if the poor don't
have incentives,

00:08:06.330 --> 00:08:08.610
they'll be a burden
on the rest of us,

00:08:08.610 --> 00:08:11.250
and we just shouldn't have that.

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:13.843
People on the state side
might say, no, no, no.

00:08:13.843 --> 00:08:16.260
You've got to take care of the
poor, it's simple humanity.

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:18.150
Forget all the incentives.

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:20.400
Those are ideological
statements.

00:08:20.400 --> 00:08:23.460
Those are statements about
how the government, how

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:27.690
the society, how the community,
what should it work to do?

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:30.820
And how best to get there?

00:08:30.820 --> 00:08:33.100
They don't arise--
those kinds of issues

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:36.179
don't arise in
the market, right?

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:38.340
Market economy, you're
buying, you're selling,

00:08:38.340 --> 00:08:40.710
you're pursuing your interest,
you're maximizing profit.

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.020
None of this stuff comes--

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:45.200
it may come up, but
it's not central.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:46.670
It's not central.

00:08:46.670 --> 00:08:49.820
In the political
system, it's central.

00:08:49.820 --> 00:08:52.230
So if I can do this--

00:08:52.230 --> 00:08:54.680
let me just for fun--

00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:58.340
if I've still got it.

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:00.500
No, I don't still have it--

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:01.010
wait a sec.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:02.900
Yeah, I do.

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:04.055
Just for humor.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:11.355
Let's do Howard Roark.

00:09:17.610 --> 00:09:20.153
This is a statement of ideology.

00:09:20.153 --> 00:09:20.820
