00:57:20.400 --> 00:57:23.100
it's not needed it might
be a preemptive strategy

00:57:23.100 --> 00:57:26.850
to make it radical
in one direction.

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:32.700
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Any other
defense of Cardozo's view?

00:57:32.700 --> 00:57:38.580
The power-- let me read
that one sentence again.

00:57:38.580 --> 00:57:42.450
The power is as broad as
the need that evokes it.

00:57:42.450 --> 00:57:43.223
Yeah?

00:57:43.223 --> 00:57:46.555
AUDIENCE: My problem
here is, one argument

00:57:46.555 --> 00:57:51.120
lies with wages and prices, the
people who would be affected

00:57:51.120 --> 00:57:53.130
is the general public.

00:57:53.130 --> 00:57:56.598
And the argument is between the
market and the policymakers,

00:57:56.598 --> 00:57:58.390
but the people who are
going to be affected

00:57:58.390 --> 00:57:59.570
are the general public.

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:02.850
So let's think if we had
this debate, or we had this--

00:58:02.850 --> 00:58:05.100
if we go back to the general
public and see what's

00:58:05.100 --> 00:58:07.200
their opinion about this point.

00:58:07.200 --> 00:58:09.245
So once the public--
once people would

00:58:09.245 --> 00:58:11.700
just-- they want to
have a regular prices

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:13.870
and they want to
have regular wages.

00:58:13.870 --> 00:58:15.810
They don't want like
the price to depend

00:58:15.810 --> 00:58:19.020
on the decision of people
who own these companies

00:58:19.020 --> 00:58:20.520
or people who run the market.

00:58:20.520 --> 00:58:22.478
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So
most people, you think,

00:58:22.478 --> 00:58:23.940
would in fact--

00:58:23.940 --> 00:58:26.970
if you put this to a vote, put
the Constitution to one side--

00:58:26.970 --> 00:58:29.870
if you put it to a
vote and you said--

00:58:29.870 --> 00:58:32.330
and by the way,
there's another reading

00:58:32.330 --> 00:58:35.930
that's optional that gives you
a sense of how really awful

00:58:35.930 --> 00:58:39.200
it was to be a coal
miner in this period--

00:58:39.200 --> 00:58:40.407
and beyond, perhaps.

00:58:40.407 --> 00:58:41.990
If you put it to a
vote, and you said,

00:58:41.990 --> 00:58:45.050
these people have terrible
jobs, they die young,

00:58:45.050 --> 00:58:48.590
they're dirt poor,
things have gotten worse.

00:58:48.590 --> 00:58:51.415
How about we pay them a living
wage and the cost of coal

00:58:51.415 --> 00:58:52.290
goes up a little bit?

00:58:52.290 --> 00:58:53.600
You think that would pass.

00:58:53.600 --> 00:58:56.330
And that that
ought to be enough.

00:58:56.330 --> 00:58:58.940
The Constitution saying,
maybe you can't do it,

00:58:58.940 --> 00:59:00.470
maybe you can--

00:59:00.470 --> 00:59:03.870
the fact that you could get a
vote on it, which you probably

00:59:03.870 --> 00:59:04.410
could.

00:59:04.410 --> 00:59:08.370
You probably could
have in the Depression.

00:59:08.370 --> 00:59:12.180
There was a 1933 case
called Appalachian Coals,

00:59:12.180 --> 00:59:14.790
an antitrust case that
went to the same Supreme

00:59:14.790 --> 00:59:16.500
Court two years earlier.

00:59:16.500 --> 00:59:20.610
And Appalachian
Coals was an attempt

00:59:20.610 --> 00:59:23.210
by a group of coal miners--

00:59:23.210 --> 00:59:24.090
they colluded.

00:59:24.090 --> 00:59:25.140
They fixed the price.

00:59:25.140 --> 00:59:27.480
They set a minimum
price of coal,

00:59:27.480 --> 00:59:31.798
which by all the antitrust law
precedent up to that point,

00:59:31.798 --> 00:59:32.715
was just flat illegal.

00:59:32.715 --> 00:59:34.320
It was just no
question about it.

00:59:34.320 --> 00:59:36.990
Go to jail-- well, yeah--
go to jail illegal.

00:59:36.990 --> 00:59:38.940
The Supreme Court
managed to find

00:59:38.940 --> 00:59:42.130
it legal in one of the
most bizarre opinions

00:59:42.130 --> 00:59:45.810
you'll ever read
because it was the '30s.

00:59:45.810 --> 00:59:47.460
It was coal miners.

00:59:47.460 --> 00:59:49.690
These people were
in terrible shape.

00:59:49.690 --> 00:59:55.500
So you would say, if it's
such a terrible problem,

00:59:55.500 --> 00:59:58.770
there's clear popular
will, just do it.

00:59:58.770 --> 01:00:02.480
Forget about the forbidden
place, forget about the states.

01:00:02.480 --> 01:00:05.270
OK.

01:00:05.270 --> 01:00:06.770
We got that.

01:00:06.770 --> 01:00:07.520
Rebuttals?

01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:10.310
Team A, you've heard
what they said.

01:00:10.310 --> 01:00:12.815
That the power is as broad
as the need that evokes it.

01:00:12.815 --> 01:00:13.940
You're right in the middle.

01:00:13.940 --> 01:00:15.620
Remind me which team you're on?

01:00:15.620 --> 01:00:16.743
OK.

01:00:16.743 --> 01:00:17.660
You're a right-winger.

01:00:17.660 --> 01:00:18.160
All right.

01:00:18.160 --> 01:00:19.460
AUDIENCE: So I think that--

01:00:19.460 --> 01:00:21.768
like so I personally probably
agree with the statement

01:00:21.768 --> 01:00:23.810
that the coal miners were
in horrible conditions,

01:00:23.810 --> 01:00:27.120
and by putting it to a vote,
you could probably pass it.

01:00:27.120 --> 01:00:29.930
But I think that Sutherland's
position is, yeah, maybe that's

01:00:29.930 --> 01:00:30.560
true.

01:00:30.560 --> 01:00:34.070
But in many Supreme Court
cases, the basis of the decision

01:00:34.070 --> 01:00:36.300
is what has been
said in the past.

01:00:36.300 --> 01:00:38.948
And so if you pass-- if you
made this legal for this case,

01:00:38.948 --> 01:00:40.490
that in future cases,
it would, like,

01:00:40.490 --> 01:00:43.700
baby steps to the
government having

01:00:43.700 --> 01:00:45.310
full control over everything.

01:00:45.310 --> 01:00:48.170
So maybe like it would have
been right in that case,

01:00:48.170 --> 01:00:49.880
but considering the
big picture, you

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:51.650
might be going down
a road that you

01:00:51.650 --> 01:00:53.042
don't want to take any further.

01:00:53.042 --> 01:00:54.500
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
And the reason

01:00:54.500 --> 01:00:57.860
you don't want to take
it is because in 1793,

01:00:57.860 --> 01:01:01.700
the Constitution was
ratified by a bunch of guys

01:01:01.700 --> 01:01:03.920
in breaches and powdered wigs.

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:06.020
AUDIENCE: And because
you don't want

01:01:06.020 --> 01:01:09.110
to disrespect the
different corporations'

01:01:09.110 --> 01:01:11.810
own entrepreneurial creativity.

01:01:11.810 --> 01:01:13.080
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK.

01:01:13.080 --> 01:01:15.568
And the answer from this side?

01:01:15.568 --> 01:01:16.860
We're a little unbalanced here.

01:01:16.860 --> 01:01:20.130
We've got a lot of market
lovers not a lot of--

01:01:20.130 --> 01:01:26.757
Rory, stand up for the
poor suffering miners.

01:01:26.757 --> 01:01:28.090
AUDIENCE: Well, if you go back--

01:01:28.090 --> 01:01:29.650
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You've
got a forbidden place argument

01:01:29.650 --> 01:01:31.990
there, a slippery
slope, take one step,

01:01:31.990 --> 01:01:34.810
got to draw the line someplace,
we're going to draw it here.

01:01:34.810 --> 01:01:37.690
AUDIENCE: From my very poor
knowledge of the Constitution,

01:01:37.690 --> 01:01:40.840
I think it like has
clauses on eminent domain.

01:01:40.840 --> 01:01:43.300
And you could argue that the
government of certain times

01:01:43.300 --> 01:01:45.530
has the right to take
property from you.

01:01:45.530 --> 01:01:48.817
And I think recently, they even
took it from private people

01:01:48.817 --> 01:01:50.150
to give to other private people.

01:01:50.150 --> 01:01:52.722
And the Supreme Court
said that was OK.

01:01:52.722 --> 01:01:54.430
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Things are different

01:01:54.430 --> 01:01:56.595
now than they were in 1935.

01:01:56.595 --> 01:01:58.720
Let me just say-- and, boy,
was that controversial.

01:01:58.720 --> 01:01:59.520
AUDIENCE: Well, OK.

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:02.230
So another example
would be police laws

01:02:02.230 --> 01:02:04.600
are pretty tyrannical
in their own way.

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:07.630
But they're appropriate
to the crime.

01:02:07.630 --> 01:02:12.850
And so in the same way, you
could create tyrannical laws

01:02:12.850 --> 01:02:15.553
in business if they're
appropriate to the crime.

01:02:15.553 --> 01:02:17.470
And that would come from
eminent domain, which

01:02:17.470 --> 01:02:19.833
I think is from the early '90s.

01:02:19.833 --> 01:02:22.000
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Eminent
domain is a provision--

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:23.870
I'm not sure it's
in the federal--

01:02:23.870 --> 01:02:26.740
well, I think it comes
out of the common law.

01:02:26.740 --> 01:02:30.670
It's the ability of a government
to take private property

01:02:30.670 --> 01:02:33.670
for public purpose and
pay fair compensation--

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:37.160
there is a fair
compensation requirement--

01:02:37.160 --> 01:02:39.730
which is the only way you
get power lines built,

01:02:39.730 --> 01:02:42.040
or railroads, or
lots of other things.

01:02:42.040 --> 01:02:44.690
You have to assemble parcels.

01:02:44.690 --> 01:02:46.060
Yeah?

01:02:46.060 --> 01:02:48.280
AUDIENCE: I think-- sorry--

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:49.450
I'm like getting sick.

01:02:49.450 --> 01:02:52.240
Fundamentally, there is
a trade-off between--

01:02:52.240 --> 01:02:53.390
yeah, it's gross.

