I think I'm getting
better, so I don't

01:02:54.460 --> 01:02:55.668
think I'm contagious anymore.

01:02:55.668 --> 01:02:58.260
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK.

01:02:58.260 --> 01:02:59.380
Everybody now inhales.

01:02:59.380 --> 01:03:00.320
Go ahead-- sorry.

01:03:00.320 --> 01:03:02.320
AUDIENCE: There's always
going to be a trade-off

01:03:02.320 --> 01:03:04.430
between freedom and equality.

01:03:04.430 --> 01:03:07.240
And I think that like
all of this conversation

01:03:07.240 --> 01:03:10.120
is about where do you want
to fall on that scale.

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:12.860
Personally-- and I think
Sutherland would agree--

01:03:12.860 --> 01:03:15.400
that it's not OK to take
away other people's freedoms

01:03:15.400 --> 01:03:16.778
to make them more equal.

01:03:16.778 --> 01:03:18.820
You know, it would be nice
if in the whole world,

01:03:18.820 --> 01:03:20.945
everyone was fine and had
the same amount of money,

01:03:20.945 --> 01:03:24.040
and it was immaterial
because there was enough food

01:03:24.040 --> 01:03:25.660
and everyone had equal access.

01:03:25.660 --> 01:03:27.183
But that's not the case.

01:03:27.183 --> 01:03:28.600
But that doesn't
mean that you get

01:03:28.600 --> 01:03:30.970
to go around taking
away people's freedoms,

01:03:30.970 --> 01:03:33.610
and freedoms that have been
guaranteed to them, just

01:03:33.610 --> 01:03:36.460
to make other people better off.

01:03:36.460 --> 01:03:40.660
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You point
to two different conceptions

01:03:40.660 --> 01:03:41.920
of justice.

01:03:41.920 --> 01:03:45.200
There's justice in
terms of fair outcomes

01:03:45.200 --> 01:03:48.430
and there's justice in
terms of fair process.

01:03:48.430 --> 01:03:53.050
And they're fundamentally
different notions.

01:03:53.050 --> 01:03:57.250
What you're saying is, I don't
want to trample with a process

01:03:57.250 --> 01:04:00.180
that I think is fair in
order to produce, say,

01:04:00.180 --> 01:04:03.100
more equality than that
process would produce.

01:04:03.100 --> 01:04:05.350
Other people might
say, well, I'm

01:04:05.350 --> 01:04:08.050
really concerned
with inequality, say,

01:04:08.050 --> 01:04:10.780
in the United States
today, where inequality has

01:04:10.780 --> 01:04:13.010
been growing by any measure.

01:04:13.010 --> 01:04:16.420
And yeah, maybe
everything's competitive

01:04:16.420 --> 01:04:19.720
and everything's swell, but
I don't like that outcome.

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:22.120
So I'll fiddle
with it with taxes.

01:04:22.120 --> 01:04:25.060
So I'm just saying there are
these two different views.

01:04:25.060 --> 01:04:27.130
I'm not saying either
one is necessarily right.

01:04:27.130 --> 01:04:29.050
You are more of
a process person.

01:04:29.050 --> 01:04:31.150
You like a fair process.

01:04:31.150 --> 01:04:33.520
And the outcome of a
fair process is fair.

01:04:33.520 --> 01:04:36.730
Others might say, take
executive salaries.

01:04:36.730 --> 01:04:38.530
Nobody's forcing
boards of directors

01:04:38.530 --> 01:04:41.230
to pay high salaries--
they're very high.

01:04:41.230 --> 01:04:42.700
Should we do something about it?

01:04:42.700 --> 01:04:45.130
Process people say no,
outcome people say yes.

01:04:48.180 --> 01:04:49.980
Thank you.

01:04:49.980 --> 01:04:52.160
Other comments?

01:04:52.160 --> 01:04:52.660
Yeah?

01:04:52.660 --> 01:04:53.780
AUDIENCE: I think
going back to what

01:04:53.780 --> 01:04:56.560
Rory said, while I sympathize
