which strengthened

01:06:12.010 --> 01:06:13.710
the ability of unions.

01:06:13.710 --> 01:06:16.450
The only thing-- since the left
wing is being very timid over

01:06:16.450 --> 01:06:17.110
here--

01:06:17.110 --> 01:06:20.020
the only thing I would
say is these little towns

01:06:20.020 --> 01:06:25.270
in West Virginia, if you're a
miner and the mine goes bust,

01:06:25.270 --> 01:06:27.550
and you own a home,
it's worthless.

01:06:27.550 --> 01:06:31.510
So you got no job and you've
got no assets to sell to move.

01:06:31.510 --> 01:06:34.420
Yeah, you could withhold
your labor, but I mean,

01:06:34.420 --> 01:06:36.080
you don't have a lot of options.

01:06:36.080 --> 01:06:41.600
It's not a frictionless--
it's not a frictionless plane.

01:06:41.600 --> 01:06:45.760
I was involved in Washington
in the Northern Spotted Owl

01:06:45.760 --> 01:06:48.640
debate around 1990.

01:06:48.640 --> 01:06:50.620
And the issue there--

01:06:50.620 --> 01:06:53.230
one of the factors
in that debate

01:06:53.230 --> 01:06:56.410
turned on people in
small towns in Oregon

01:06:56.410 --> 01:06:59.140
who made their living
cutting down trees.

01:06:59.140 --> 01:07:04.930
If you regulated
logging sharply,

01:07:04.930 --> 01:07:07.060
they had worthless homes.

01:07:07.060 --> 01:07:09.940
And their skill was
cutting down trees.

01:07:09.940 --> 01:07:12.190
And they got no place to go.

01:07:12.190 --> 01:07:17.270
So unless you did something
to compensate them for that

01:07:17.270 --> 01:07:19.520
situation-- that was a case
where it was a government

01:07:19.520 --> 01:07:22.200
regulation, but it could
easily have been a market--

01:07:22.200 --> 01:07:24.140
they are just stuck.

01:07:24.140 --> 01:07:27.805
And you get alcoholism, and
child abuse, and spousal abuse,

01:07:27.805 --> 01:07:29.180
and all of the
things that happen

01:07:29.180 --> 01:07:30.470
when communities break down.

01:07:30.470 --> 01:07:34.748
So it's not-- it's not pretty.

01:07:34.748 --> 01:07:36.290
I'm trying to help
the left over here

01:07:36.290 --> 01:07:38.750
with a little
tear-jerking argument.

01:07:38.750 --> 01:07:41.890
But-- yeah?

01:07:41.890 --> 01:07:44.377
AUDIENCE: I was going to say
just for the left-wing side,

01:07:44.377 --> 01:07:45.210
I was going to say--

01:07:45.210 --> 01:07:45.680
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Please.

01:07:45.680 --> 01:07:47.840
AUDIENCE: --you get
back into the argument

01:07:47.840 --> 01:07:51.630
that electricity does
cross interstate lines.

01:07:51.630 --> 01:07:54.660
So Congress does have the
power to regulate these laws,

01:07:54.660 --> 01:07:59.070
regardless of how ideologically
you feel about it.

01:07:59.070 --> 01:08:01.505
Constitutionally, it
should be allowed.

01:08:01.505 --> 01:08:02.880
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So you'd say

01:08:02.880 --> 01:08:05.820
that this whole direct/indirect
thing that Sutherland

01:08:05.820 --> 01:08:07.480
was writing--

01:08:07.480 --> 01:08:10.350
which he couldn't define
other than to mush around

01:08:10.350 --> 01:08:12.150
for a couple of pages--

01:08:12.150 --> 01:08:14.580
is really not a distinction.

01:08:14.580 --> 01:08:15.660
That if it affects--

01:08:15.660 --> 01:08:19.800
it affects, and there's no
direct/indirect sensible

01:08:19.800 --> 01:08:23.310
distinction, and wages
affect prices of coal.

01:08:23.310 --> 01:08:24.005
Yeah?

01:08:24.005 --> 01:08:24.630
AUDIENCE: Sure.

01:08:24.630 --> 01:08:27.359
I'm like a fair
believer in the markets,

01:08:27.359 --> 01:08:29.580
but I'm sitting on this
side, so I figured I'd--

01:08:29.580 --> 01:08:30.955
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Do your job.

01:08:30.955 --> 01:08:31.830
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:08:31.830 --> 01:08:34.590
And it was pertaining to the--

01:08:34.590 --> 01:08:36.090
to having a fair process.

01:08:36.090 --> 01:08:38.970
And I mean, I believe
in a fair process,

01:08:38.970 --> 01:08:44.279
but it's always like the kind
of recursive nature in the sense

01:08:44.279 --> 01:08:47.040
that you have to establish
a fair playground in order

01:08:47.040 --> 01:08:49.770
for the outcome of a
fair process to be fair.

01:08:49.770 --> 01:08:52.890
And perhaps in this case,
when shit's hitting the fan,

01:08:52.890 --> 01:08:56.760
you really need to try and
have the government interfere

01:08:56.760 --> 01:09:01.590
and create somewhat equality so
that the process is then fair.

01:09:01.590 --> 01:09:04.410
And from then on, you can
then say, well, you know,

01:09:04.410 --> 01:09:06.660
we've allowed everyone
with the same--

01:09:06.660 --> 01:09:09.180
we've tried to give everyone
the same kind of benefits

01:09:09.180 --> 01:09:10.710
or the same opportunities.

01:09:10.710 --> 01:09:13.109
And from here, whoever
takes it, well,

01:09:13.109 --> 01:09:15.558
is then a CEO and is making
money and who doesn't isn't.

01:09:15.558 --> 01:09:17.850
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: And what
do the folks on this side

01:09:17.850 --> 01:09:19.859
say in response to that?

01:09:19.859 --> 01:09:21.910
Somebody who hasn't spoken.

01:09:21.910 --> 01:09:22.410
Max?

01:09:22.410 --> 01:09:24.410
AUDIENCE: I think it's a
big issue with conflict

01:09:24.410 --> 01:09:25.575
of interest.

01:09:25.575 --> 01:09:27.450
In this situation, you'll
have the government

01:09:27.450 --> 01:09:31.830
that may have been trying to
act in the interest of workers,

01:09:31.830 --> 01:09:34.330
in labor rights,
things of that nature.

01:09:34.330 --> 01:09:36.000
But that might not
always be the case.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:37.500
We've been looking
at the government

01:09:37.500 --> 01:09:39.870
as kind of this benevolent
power that's trying

01:09:39.870 --> 01:09:41.550
to improve workers rights.

01:09:41.550 --> 01:09:45.450
But in the future, you'll
have all these congressmen

01:09:45.450 --> 01:09:48.779
from different states,
and legislation passed

01:09:48.779 --> 01:09:50.529
might not be in the
interest of one state.

01:09:50.529 --> 01:09:52.237
It might be an interest
to another state.

01:09:52.237 --> 01:09:54.000
And if there's a
majority, you end up

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:57.370
affecting one state in the
interest of many others.

01:09:57.370 --> 01:09:59.520
And so it's where the--

01:09:59.520 --> 01:10:02.560
if it doesn't affect interstate
commerce-- and in this case,

01:10:02.560 --> 01:10:04.590
the argument was that
production does not

01:10:04.590 --> 01:10:07.320
affect interstate commerce--
the federal government

01:10:07.320 --> 01:10:09.362
shouldn't have the power
to regulate it because

01:10:09.362 --> 01:10:10.570
of that conflict of interest.

01:10:10.570 --> 01:10:12.670
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So you think we draw

01:10:12.670 --> 01:10:15.390
a simple, clear bright line.

01:10:15.390 --> 01:10:17.880
There's a lot of good stuff on
the other side of that line,

01:10:17.880 --> 01:10:20.250
but there's a lot
of bad stuff there.

01:10:20.250 --> 01:10:22.128
Sutherland's forbidden
place is on that side.

01:10:22.128 --> 01:10:23.670
AUDIENCE: I think
one of the comments

01:10:23.670 --> 01:10:27.120
was the necessary evil
of an open market, where

01:10:27.120 --> 01:10:30.690
while the government has
to accept that there are

01:10:30.690 --> 01:10:35.040
some evils, maybe unfair labor
standards that they can't deal,

01:10:35.040 --> 01:10:37.793
with but to have a truly
fair and open market,

01:10:37.793 --> 01:10:39.960
you need to let those evils
exist and let the states

01:10:39.960 --> 01:10:41.823
deal with them if they
think it's proper.

01:10:41.823 --> 01:10:43.740
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: And
if I were Sutherland,

01:10:43.740 --> 01:10:47.820
I might say, look, today
it's the poor coal miners--

01:10:47.820 --> 01:10:51.060
tomorrow, it's the poor
investment bankers.

01:10:51.060 --> 01:10:53.070
And if we get
votes in Congress--

01:10:53.070 --> 01:10:56.072
God knows how-- that investment
bankers' wages are too low

01:10:56.072 --> 01:10:57.780
and they need to be
increased, and if you

01:10:57.780 --> 01:11:00.000
let me fix a wage
for coal miners,

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:02.490
I'll fix a weight for
investment bankers tomorrow.

01:11:02.490 --> 01:11:05.110
And we know that's nuts
and we need a wall.

01:11:05.110 --> 01:11:05.610
OK.

01:11:05.610 --> 01:11:07.570
Let me bring it to a close.

01:11:07.570 --> 01:11:08.340
Thank you all.

01:11:08.340 --> 01:11:09.180
This was good.

01:11:09.180 --> 01:11:12.930
You aired a lot of
the main issues.

01:11:12.930 --> 01:11:15.360
Let me just tell
you what happened.

01:11:15.360 --> 01:11:19.410
After this, Roosevelt found
this string of defeats--

01:11:19.410 --> 01:11:22.950
this was just another
defeat for the New Deal--

01:11:22.950 --> 01:11:24.210
very frustrating.

01:11:24.210 --> 01:11:28.650
And in 1937, he
issued a bill which

01:11:28.650 --> 01:11:31.380
would have let him appoint
more justices to the Supreme

01:11:31.380 --> 01:11:33.990
Court, the so-called
court-packing bill.

01:11:38.180 --> 01:11:42.420
Two months later, the
court reversed itself

01:11:42.420 --> 01:11:46.050
on the federal government's
ability to regulate wages.

01:11:46.050 --> 01:11:47.550
One judge switched.

01:11:47.550 --> 01:11:51.270
Carter versus Carter Coal
was a 5 to 4 decision.

01:11:51.270 --> 01:11:53.940
In 1937, they switched.

01:11:53.940 --> 01:11:57.810
This was referred to as the
switch in time that saved

01:11:57.810 --> 01:12:00.510
nine-- nine justices
in the Supreme Court--

01:12:00.510 --> 01:12:02.010
clever language.

01:12:02.010 --> 01:12:06.120
The Court says, however,
they'd taken the vote earlier.

01:12:06.120 --> 01:12:08.670
The bill died in any
case in the Senate

01:12:08.670 --> 01:12:11.250
in July, which is why
we still have nine

01:12:11.250 --> 01:12:15.440
justices on the Supreme Court.

01:12:15.440 --> 01:12:17.960
Who has won historically,
Sutherland or Cardozo?

01:12:22.130 --> 01:12:22.880
AUDIENCE: Cardozo.

01:12:22.880 --> 01:12:23.870
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Cardozo.

01:12:23.870 --> 01:12:25.287
Do we have a federal
minimum wage?

01:12:25.287 --> 01:12:26.210
Yes.

01:12:26.210 --> 01:12:27.210
Scott?

01:12:27.210 --> 01:12:29.418
AUDIENCE: I would say that's
different than this case

01:12:29.418 --> 01:12:32.120
because the minimum wage
law isn't just for coal.

01:12:32.120 --> 01:12:32.530
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
That's true.

01:12:32.530 --> 01:12:34.580
AUDIENCE: --coal, it
gives it every generation.

01:12:34.580 --> 01:12:37.880
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: But the
fundamental question of does

01:12:37.880 --> 01:12:40.340
the Commerce Clause stop--

01:12:40.340 --> 01:12:43.910
that fundamental question--
stop the federal government

01:12:43.910 --> 01:12:46.310
from regulating things
that occur inside states,

01:12:46.310 --> 01:12:50.060
like paying wages
or setting safety

01:12:50.060 --> 01:12:54.470
conditions for this room,
or lots of other things?

01:12:54.470 --> 01:12:57.780
Cardozo won.

01:12:57.780 --> 01:13:02.430
The view, at least
until recently,

01:13:02.430 --> 01:13:05.790
was that if you could find an
impact on interstate commerce,

01:13:05.790 --> 01:13:09.160
the federal government
could regulate it.

01:13:09.160 --> 01:13:14.170
That's disputed now, and we
have a Supreme Court that

01:13:14.170 --> 01:13:16.550
is tilting the other direction.

01:13:16.550 --> 01:13:21.910
But the run of
decisions from the '30s

01:13:21.910 --> 01:13:26.020
forward has largely been in
Cardozo's direction, at least

01:13:26.020 --> 01:13:29.890
as regards the Commerce Clause.

01:13:29.890 --> 01:13:34.670
But issues like this don't
get settled permanently.

01:13:34.670 --> 01:13:36.230
The pendulum may swing.

01:13:36.230 --> 01:13:40.670
There's a lot more concern
with states' rights, as I say.

01:13:40.670 --> 01:13:42.590
To actually say the
federal government

01:13:42.590 --> 01:13:45.590
should just fix
the electric system

01:13:45.590 --> 01:13:47.420
is to get laughed out of town.

01:13:47.420 --> 01:13:51.680
It's a state
function, full stop.

01:13:51.680 --> 01:13:53.333
OK.

01:13:53.333 --> 01:13:55.250
I think we've covered
what there was to cover.

01:13:55.250 --> 01:13:56.900
Questions, comments, reactions?

01:14:00.310 --> 01:14:00.810
Thank you.

01:14:00.810 --> 01:14:03.890
I'll see you all tomorrow,
believe it or not.